Say we want to build a HOC to automatically inject onClick handler (which executes `blur`) into a wrapped component. To achieve this, we should make sure that the wrapped component complies to following:

1. accepts `onClick` prop and correctly handles it (in my case, actually accepts HTMLAttributes&lt;NodeType&gt;, i.e. the component is either `emotion`&#39;s StyledComponent or a component with custom styles that forwards all props to an intrinsic JSX element)
2. forwards ref object to underlying intrinsic JSX element.

This is my current implementation:

```typescript
type NodeType&lt;Props&gt; = Props extends HTMLAttributes&lt;infer _NodeType&gt; &amp; ClassAttributes&lt;infer _NodeType&gt;
  ? _NodeType
  : never

export const withAutoBlur = &lt;Props extends HTMLAttributes&lt;HTMLElement&gt;&gt;
  (Component: FC&lt;Props &amp; ClassAttributes&lt;NodeType&lt;Props&gt;&gt;&gt;) =&gt; {
  const WrappedWithAutoBlur: React.FC&lt;Props&gt; = (props: Props) =&gt; {
    type HTMLNode = NodeType&lt;Props&gt;

    const { onClick } = props

    const ref = useRef&lt;HTMLNode&gt;(null)
    const clickHandler = useCallback((e: React.MouseEvent&lt;HTMLNode&gt;) =&gt; {
      ref.current &amp;&amp; ref.current.blur()

      onClick &amp;&amp; onClick(e)
    }, [onClick])

    return (
      &lt;Component {...props} ref={ref} onClick={clickHandler} /&gt;
    )
  }

  return WrappedWithAutoBlur
}
```

This implementation silences all type warnings, so it *kind of* works. There are two issues though:

1. component that accepts no props, that is, has props type of empty object (`{}`), passes the generic type constraint `extends HTMLAttributes&lt;HTMLElement&gt;` since all properties of `HTMLAttributes&lt;HTMLElement&gt;` are optional
2. if you pass a functional component into this HOC that actually doesn&#39;t forward ref, TS thinks it&#39;s perfectly fine. React doesn&#39;t think the same, though.

```
Warning: Function components cannot be given refs. Attempts to access this ref will fail. Did you mean to use React.forwardRef()?
```

Any ideas on how to fix this?

